**CIVIL ENGINEERING DRAWINGS**

Professional Reading & Material Take-Off Guide

*For Residential, Commercial & Industrial/Infrastructure Projects*

*A Complete Beginner\'s Reference*

**SECTION 1: Understanding the Drawing Set**

Before you can perform a material take-off, you must first understand
what a civil drawing set is and how it is organized. A full set of civil
engineering drawings tells the complete story of everything that needs
to happen at a site before vertical construction (buildings, structures)
can begin.

**1.1 What Is a Civil Drawing Set?**

A civil drawing set is a collection of technical drawings prepared by a
licensed civil engineer. Each sheet has a specific purpose and covers a
different aspect of the site work. Think of it like a recipe book ---
each section covers a different course of the meal.

**1.2 Standard Sheet Types & What They Cover**

  -------------------------- --------------------------------------------
  **Sheet Type /             What It Shows
  Abbreviation**             

  **Cover Sheet / C-0.0**    Project title, location, sheet index,
                             general notes, vicinity map, and code
                             references

  **Existing Conditions /    Current state of the site: existing
  C-1.0**                    topography, utilities, structures, trees,
                             and features to be removed or protected

  **Demolition Plan /        What needs to be torn out, removed, or
  C-2.0**                    demolished before new work begins

  **Site Plan / C-3.0**      The overall layout of the new site: building
                             footprints, parking, drives, property lines,
                             and setbacks

  **Grading Plan / C-4.0**   Proposed elevations, slopes, cut and fill
                             areas, and drainage flow directions

  **Drainage / Storm Plan /  Storm sewer lines, inlets,
  C-5.0**                    detention/retention basins, pipes, and
                             outfalls

  **Utility Plan / C-6.0**   Underground utilities: water, sewer, gas,
                             electric, telecom, and irrigation

  **Erosion & Sediment       Temporary controls to prevent sediment
  Control / C-7.0**          runoff during construction (silt fence, rock
                             check dams, inlet protection)

  **Road / Paving Plan /     Road widths, paving types, curb and gutter,
  C-8.0**                    sidewalks, and pavement sections

  **Details / C-9.0+**       Close-up drawings of specific construction
                             elements: manhole sections, pipe bedding,
                             curb types, pavement sections
  -------------------------- --------------------------------------------

**1.3 The Title Block --- Your First Stop on Every Sheet**

Every sheet has a title block, usually in the bottom-right corner.
Always read it first. It contains:

  -------------------------- --------------------------------------------
  **Title Block Item**       Why It Matters

  **Project Name & Address** Confirms you have the right set of drawings

  **Sheet Number & Title**   Tells you what discipline and sequence this
                             sheet is

  **Scale**                  Critical --- you cannot measure anything
                             without knowing the scale

  **Revision Block**         Shows any changes made after original issue;
                             always use the latest revision

  **Engineer\'s Seal &       Confirms the drawings are official and
  Signature**                approved

  **Drawing Date**           Ensures you are working from the current
                             version
  -------------------------- --------------------------------------------

**1.4 Reading the Scale**

Scale is one of the most important concepts for a beginner. It tells you
the relationship between a distance on paper and the actual distance in
the field.

-   1\" = 20\' means 1 inch on the drawing equals 20 feet in real life

-   1\" = 40\' is a smaller scale (things look smaller on paper)

-   1\" = 10\' is a larger scale (things look bigger, more detail shown)

Always use a scale ruler (engineer\'s scale) to measure distances on
drawings. Never use a regular ruler. If you need to take a measurement
off a printed drawing, first confirm the print was made at 100% (full
scale) --- not enlarged or reduced.

**SECTION 2: Reading the Grading Plan (Excavation & Earthwork)**

The grading plan is the foundation of your earthwork take-off. It shows
you the existing ground elevations and the proposed (finished) ground
elevations --- and the difference between the two is what you have to
move.

**2.1 Contour Lines**

Contour lines connect points of equal elevation. Learning to read them
is essential:

-   Lines close together = steep slope

-   Lines far apart = gentle slope or flat ground

-   Circles (closed contours) = a hill (contours increase toward center)
    or a depression/swale (contours decrease toward center)

-   Index contours are drawn heavier/darker and labeled with their
    elevation (e.g., 100\', 105\', 110\')

-   Intermediate contours are the lighter lines between index contours

**2.2 Existing vs. Proposed Elevations**

  -------------------------- --------------------------------------------
  **Symbol / Notation**      What It Means

  **Dashed contour lines**   Existing (existing ground before any work)

  **Solid contour lines**    Proposed (finished ground after grading)

  **103.5 (number in         Existing spot elevation at that point
  parentheses)**             

  **103.5 (number not in     Proposed finished elevation
  parentheses)**             

  **FF = 105.00**            Finished Floor elevation of building

  **TC = 102.50**            Top of Curb elevation

  **FL = 101.80**            Flow Line (bottom of pipe or channel)

  **TW / BW**                Top of Wall / Bottom of Wall (for retaining
                             walls)

  **+/- symbol**             Cut (+) means you are removing soil; Fill
                             (-) means you are adding soil
  -------------------------- --------------------------------------------

**2.3 Cut & Fill --- The Core of Earthwork**

Cut is soil you remove (excavate). Fill is soil you bring in or
relocate. The goal of a balanced earthwork site is to cut and fill equal
amounts so you do not pay to haul excess material off-site or import
material.

1.  Identify the existing elevation at a point (dashed contour or
    existing spot elevation)

2.  Identify the proposed elevation at the same point (solid contour or
    proposed spot elevation)

3.  Subtract: Proposed minus Existing = Net change

4.  If the result is negative (lower than existing) = CUT (excavation
    required)

5.  If the result is positive (higher than existing) = FILL (material
    needs to be added)

Example: Existing elevation = 108.5\', Proposed elevation = 105.0\'. Net
= -3.5 feet. This area requires 3.5 feet of cut (excavation).

**2.4 Calculating Earthwork Volume (Average End Area Method)**

To convert cut/fill depths to cubic yards (the unit used for estimating
and bidding):

-   Divide the site into a grid (typically 50\' x 50\' or 100\' x 100\'
    squares)

-   Calculate the average cut or fill depth at each grid square

-   Volume (cubic feet) = Area of grid square x Average depth

-   Convert to cubic yards: divide by 27 (there are 27 cubic feet in 1
    cubic yard)

-   Apply a swell factor: excavated soil swells 15-30% when removed
    (bank cubic yards vs. loose cubic yards)

Tip: On larger projects, civil engineers often provide a cut/fill
quantity summary on the grading plan. Always check for this note before
manually calculating --- it saves significant time.

**SECTION 3: Reading the Utility Plan (Underground Utilities)**

The utility plan shows all underground systems that must be installed
before the site is ready for vertical construction. Each utility type
has its own standard line type, color code, and symbology.

**3.1 Standard Utility Line Types & Colors**

  -------------------------- --------------------------------------------
  **Utility Type**           Standard Color / Line Type on Drawings

  **Potable Water (Water     Blue solid line --- W or WM label
  Main)**                    

  **Sanitary Sewer           Green solid line --- SS or SAN label
  (Gravity)**                

  **Sanitary Sewer (Force    Green dashed line --- FM label
  Main/Pressure)**           

  **Storm Drainage**         Dark blue or gray line --- SD or STM label

  **Gas Main**               Yellow line --- G or GAS label

  **Electric (Underground)** Red line --- E or ELEC label

  **Telecommunications /     Orange line --- T, TEL, or FIBER label
  Fiber**                    

  **Irrigation Main**        Purple or light blue --- IRR label

  **Reclaimed / Recycled     Purple dashed line --- RW or RCL label
  Water**                    
  -------------------------- --------------------------------------------

Note: Colors may vary by engineering firm. Always check the drawing
legend (usually on the cover sheet or utility plan) to confirm the color
and line type conventions used on that specific project.

**3.2 Key Utility Symbols to Know**

  -------------------------- --------------------------------------------
  **Symbol**                 What It Represents

  **Circle with a cross      Manhole (sanitary or storm)
  inside**                   

  **Square or rectangle      Valve box (water or gas shutoff valve)
  symbol**                   

  **Triangle or diamond      Cleanout (sanitary sewer access point)
  symbol**                   

  **CB or DI inside a        Catch Basin or Drop Inlet (storm drainage)
  square**                   

  **FH symbol**              Fire Hydrant

  **MH-1, MH-2\...           Manhole designation --- referenced in the
  numbering**                pipe schedule table

  **Rim = 104.20**           Top elevation of manhole cover

  **Inv = 98.45**            Invert elevation --- bottom inside of pipe
                             at that point

  **Arrow on pipe line**     Flow direction of gravity pipe
  -------------------------- --------------------------------------------

**3.3 Reading the Pipe Schedule / Utility Table**

Most utility plans include a pipe schedule or utility table that lists
every pipe segment with its specifications. This is critical for your
material take-off. It typically includes:

-   From structure number (e.g., MH-1)

-   To structure number (e.g., MH-2)

-   Pipe diameter (e.g., 8\" or 12\")

-   Pipe material (e.g., PVC SDR-35, RCP Class III, HDPE)

-   Length of pipe (e.g., 125 LF)

-   Slope (e.g., 0.50%)

-   Upstream and downstream invert elevations

From this table you can extract exact pipe lengths, diameters, and
materials for your take-off without having to scale every pipe run off
the drawing.

**3.4 Common Underground Utility Materials by Type**

  -------------------------- --------------------------------------------
  **Utility**                Common Pipe/Conduit Materials

  **Water Main               PVC C-900, Ductile Iron (DI), HDPE
  (Pressurized)**            

  **Sanitary Sewer           PVC SDR-35, PVC SDR-26, Vitrified Clay Pipe
  (Gravity)**                (VCP)

  **Sanitary Sewer (Force    PVC C-900, HDPE, Ductile Iron
  Main)**                    

  **Storm Drainage (Small)** PVC, Corrugated HDPE (ADS N-12)

  **Storm Drainage (Large)** Reinforced Concrete Pipe (RCP), Box Culvert

  **Electric / Telecom**     PVC Schedule 40 or 80 conduit (EMT
                             underground)

  **Gas Main**               Yellow MDPE (Medium Density Polyethylene),
                             Steel
  -------------------------- --------------------------------------------

**SECTION 4: Reading the Storm Drainage Plan**

Storm drainage controls rainwater runoff. The storm drainage system
collects surface runoff and carries it to an outfall, detention basin,
or existing municipal system. It is entirely separate from the sanitary
sewer system.

**4.1 Key Storm Drainage Components**

  -------------------------- --------------------------------------------
  **Component**              Description & What to Take Off

  **Catch Basin (CB)**       Collects surface runoff from paved areas.
                             Count each unit. Note grate type
                             (traffic-rated vs. pedestrian).

  **Drop Inlet (DI)**        Similar to catch basin but typically in a
                             grass/landscaped area. Count each unit.

  **Storm Manhole (SMH)**    Access structure for storm pipe. Count each
                             unit; note rim and invert elevations.

  **Storm Pipe**             Underground pipe carrying collected runoff.
                             Take off linear feet by diameter and
                             material.

  **Flared End Section       Open end of pipe at outfall into ditch or
  (FES)**                    water body. Count each unit.

  **Headwall**               Concrete structure at pipe outfall for
                             erosion protection. Count or measure volume.

  **Detention Pond**         Holds stormwater temporarily to control
                             runoff rate. Take off excavation volume and
                             embankment.

  **Retention Pond**         Holds stormwater permanently (has permanent
                             pool). Take off excavation volume.

  **Swale / Bio-swale**      Vegetated channel for drainage. Take off
                             linear feet and cross-section dimensions.

  **Riprap / Erosion         Stone protection at outfalls and slopes.
  Control**                  Take off square feet or cubic yards.
  -------------------------- --------------------------------------------

**4.2 Reading Storm Pipe Profiles**

Most storm drainage plans include a pipe profile view --- a
cross-sectional side view showing the pipe running underground. This is
critical because it shows:

-   The actual depth of the pipe below finished grade at each point

-   Conflicts with other utilities (crossings)

-   Required pipe slope for gravity flow

-   Cover depth (soil above top of pipe) to check minimums

Minimum cover for storm pipe is typically 2 feet, but always check
project specifications and local standards.

**SECTION 5: Reading the Road & Paving Plans**

Road and paving plans show all horizontal paving, curb, gutter,
sidewalk, and the pavement section (the layer cake of materials beneath
the asphalt or concrete surface).

**5.1 Pavement Section / Typical Section**

The most important detail on the paving plan is the Typical Section ---
a cross-sectional view of the road showing every layer from top to
bottom. Always find this detail first. It will tell you:

  -------------------------- --------------------------------------------
  **Layer**                  Typical Material & Thickness

  **Surface Course (Top)**   Asphalt Concrete (AC) --- typically 1.5\" to
                             2\" for residential, 2\" to 3\" for
                             commercial

  **Binder/Base Course**     Asphalt Concrete --- typically 2\" to 3\"

  **Aggregate Base Course    Crushed stone/gravel --- typically 4\" to
  (ABC)**                    8\" residential, 6\" to 12\"
                             commercial/industrial

  **Subbase (if specified)** Select fill or granular material --- varies

  **Subgrade**               Native soil --- may require compaction or
                             stabilization

  **Geotextile Fabric (if    Woven fabric layer between subgrade and base
  specified)**               --- used when subgrade is weak
  -------------------------- --------------------------------------------

For concrete paving (typically used for heavy industrial or high-traffic
areas): PCC (Portland Cement Concrete) slab thickness typically ranges
from 4\" (pedestrian) to 6\"--8\" (vehicular) to 10\"--12\" (heavy
industrial).

**5.2 Road Geometry Terms**

  -------------------------- --------------------------------------------
  **Term / Abbreviation**    Definition

  **ROW (Right-of-Way)**     The total width of land dedicated for the
                             roadway, including travel lanes, curb,
                             sidewalk, and utilities

  **FC / Face of Curb**      The vertical front face of the curb --- this
                             is where pavement width is typically
                             measured

  **BC / Back of Curb**      The back side of the curb --- edge of paved
                             surface including gutter pan

  **CL / Centerline**        The centerline of the road

  **EOP / Edge of Pavement** Where paving ends (used on roads without
                             curb)

  **Crown**                  The high point of the road (center or one
                             side) that causes water to drain to the
                             edges

  **Cross Slope**            The slope of the road perpendicular to
                             travel direction --- typically 2% for
                             drainage

  **Superelevation**         Banking of the road on curves to counteract
                             centrifugal force

  **Curb & Gutter (C&G)**    The combined concrete curb and gutter
                             channel at the edge of pavement

  **Sidewalk**               Pedestrian path --- typically 4\"--6\"
                             concrete, 4\'--6\' wide
  -------------------------- --------------------------------------------

**5.3 Paving Take-Off Quantities**

-   Asphalt & Concrete: Measured in Square Yards (SY) or Square Feet
    (SF), then converted to tons for asphalt

-   Curb & Gutter: Measured in Linear Feet (LF)

-   Sidewalk: Measured in Square Feet (SF) or Linear Feet (LF)

-   Aggregate Base: Measured in Square Yards x thickness, converted to
    cubic yards or tons

-   Subgrade preparation: Measured in Square Yards

Asphalt tonnage conversion: (Area in SY) x (thickness in inches / 12) x
110 lbs/CF x 27 CF/CY / 2000 lbs/ton. Or use the simplified rule of
thumb: 1 inch of asphalt over 1 square yard weighs approximately 110 lbs
(0.055 tons).

**SECTION 6: Performing the Material Take-Off --- Step by Step**

A material take-off (MTO) is a systematic count and measurement of every
item of work shown on the drawings. It is the foundation of your cost
estimate. Follow this workflow for every project.

**6.1 The Take-Off Workflow**

6.  Assemble the complete drawing set --- confirm you have the latest
    revision of every sheet

7.  Read the Cover Sheet first --- note the project scope, applicable
    codes, and any general notes

8.  Review the Site Plan to understand the overall layout before diving
    into details

9.  Work sheet by sheet in order --- do not jump around or you will miss
    items

10. Use a consistent color-coding system --- highlight each item as you
    count/measure it so nothing is counted twice

11. Organize your take-off by CSI Division or work category (earthwork,
    utilities, paving, etc.)

12. Always note the unit of measure for each item (LF, SF, CY, EA, TON,
    etc.)

13. Apply waste factors for materials that have cutting loss or breakage

14. Cross-check quantities --- measure the same item two ways if
    possible

15. Summarize all quantities in a formatted take-off sheet before
    pricing

**6.2 Standard Units of Measure**

  -------------------------- --------------------------------------------
  **Unit**                   Used For

  **LF (Linear Feet)**       Pipe, curb & gutter, fence, conduit,
                             drainage channel

  **SF (Square Feet)**       Sidewalk, concrete flatwork, geotextile
                             fabric, erosion control matting

  **SY (Square Yards)**      Asphalt paving, aggregate base, subgrade
                             prep, seeding/sodding

  **CY (Cubic Yards)**       Excavation, fill, concrete, rip-rap, gravel
                             backfill

  **EA (Each)**              Manholes, catch basins, valves, fire
                             hydrants, signs, trees

  **TON**                    Asphalt concrete, aggregate base, rip-rap,
                             stone

  **LS (Lump Sum)**          Mobilization, bonds, clearing & grubbing
                             (sometimes)

  **AC (Acres)**             Clearing & grubbing, seeding, erosion
                             control
  -------------------------- --------------------------------------------

**6.3 Take-Off by Work Category**

**Clearing & Grubbing**

-   Measure total area to be cleared in Acres (AC)

-   Note any specific trees to be removed --- count each (EA) and note
    trunk diameter

-   Note any structures, pavement, or features to be demolished

**Rough Grading / Earthwork**

-   Calculate total Cut volume (CY) from grading plan

-   Calculate total Fill volume (CY) from grading plan

-   Determine if excess cut material needs to be hauled off-site
    (export) or if fill is needed (import)

-   Note any unsuitable material (organics, soft spots) requiring
    over-excavation

-   Include compaction testing requirements from specifications

**Storm Drainage**

-   List every pipe segment: Size (diameter), Material, Length (LF)

-   Count every structure: Catch Basins, Drop Inlets, Storm Manholes,
    Headwalls (EA)

-   Measure trench excavation volume for each pipe (CY) --- include
    bedding stone and backfill

-   Count flared end sections, outlet protection riprap (CY or TON)

**Sanitary Sewer**

-   List every pipe segment: Size, Material, Length (LF)

-   Count every manhole (EA) --- note depth, type, and frame/cover

-   Count cleanouts (EA)

-   Note any service laterals to building connections

**Water Main**

-   List every pipe segment: Size, Material, Length (LF) --- include
    fittings (elbows, tees, reducers)

-   Count fire hydrant assemblies (EA)

-   Count gate valves and valve boxes (EA)

-   Count service connections / taps (EA)

**Paving & Surfacing**

-   Calculate total paving area (SY) by pavement type and section

-   Calculate curb & gutter (LF) by type (vertical, roll, mountable,
    etc.)

-   Calculate sidewalk area (SF) or length (LF)

-   Calculate aggregate base (SY x thickness = CY, then convert to tons)

-   Calculate asphalt tonnage by layer

**Erosion & Sediment Control**

-   Silt fence (LF)

-   Construction entrance (EA or SY)

-   Inlet protection devices (EA)

-   Seeding and mulching (AC or SY)

**SECTION 7: Key Differences by Project Type**

**7.1 Residential Development**

-   Smaller scale, more lots to subdivide --- plan carefully around lot
    lines

-   Individual utility services to each lot (water meter, sewer lateral)

-   Shallower utilities generally --- less rock excavation risk

-   Residential road sections typically lighter (thinner pavement)

-   Drainage often uses swales and smaller pipes vs. large storm systems

-   Homebuilder associations may have specific standards to follow

**7.2 Commercial Development**

-   Heavier pavement sections --- design for truck traffic

-   Large parking lots --- significant paving quantities

-   Detention ponds often required for stormwater management

-   Multiple utility services: domestic water, fire suppression water,
    grease trap connections

-   ADA compliance is critical --- accessible routes, ramps, parking

-   Drives and entrances must be coordinated with local DOT/traffic
    engineering

**7.3 Industrial / Infrastructure**

-   Heaviest pavement sections --- often concrete over 8\" thick for
    truck and heavy equipment loads

-   Large utility mains --- 12\", 16\", 24\" and larger pipes

-   Complex grading for drainage around large buildings and truck courts

-   Significant earthwork --- cut and fill volumes often in tens of
    thousands of cubic yards

-   May include rail spurs, truck scales, fueling stations, detention
    systems

-   Strict environmental requirements --- SWPPP (Stormwater Pollution
    Prevention Plan) required

-   Higher risk of underground conflicts --- more utility locating and
    potholing required

**SECTION 8: Reading the Project Specifications**

The drawings show WHERE and HOW MUCH. The specifications (\"specs\")
tell you the quality, materials, and standards required. You cannot
complete a take-off without reading both.

**8.1 What Specifications Cover**

-   Approved materials and manufacturers (e.g., \"PVC pipe shall be
    SDR-35 conforming to ASTM D3034\")

-   Minimum compaction requirements (e.g., \"95% Standard Proctor
    density\")

-   Pipe bedding requirements (type and depth of stone under pipe)

-   Testing requirements (pressure tests, mandrel tests, compaction
    tests)

-   Pavement mix designs (asphalt gradation, binder type)

-   Concrete mix design (PSI strength, slump, air entrainment)

**8.2 Common Specification Red Flags for Take-Offs**

-   Import fill requirements --- if native soil cannot be used as fill,
    you must include imported select fill

-   Over-excavation requirements for unsuitable soils --- adds to
    excavation and fill volumes

-   Special bedding requirements --- 4\" or 6\" of #57 stone under all
    pipes adds significant material cost

-   Dewatering requirements --- if groundwater is expected, you may need
    to include dewatering in scope

-   Geotextile fabric requirements --- often required under aggregate
    base in poor soil conditions

