**SECTION 10: Pro Tips & Common Beginner Mistakes**

**10.1 Pro Tips**

-   Always work from the most current drawing revision --- check the
    revision block on every sheet before you start

-   Read all general notes before starting your take-off --- they often
    contain critical information that overrides what is shown
    graphically

-   When in doubt, take off more rather than less --- it is easier to
    reduce quantities than to go back and add missed items

-   Verify your scale before measuring --- print at 100% or use digital
    take-off software with the correct scale set

-   Coordinate with the mechanical/plumbing/electrical team --- some
    underground utilities may be on their drawings, not civil

-   Ask for a geotechnical report (soil boring report) --- it tells you
    what soil conditions and rock exist underground, which dramatically
    affects excavation cost

-   Look for addenda --- any changes issued after the original bid set
    supersede the original drawings

**10.2 Common Beginner Mistakes to Avoid**

-   Scaling off an incorrectly printed drawing --- always verify scale
    with a known dimension first

-   Missing items shown only in the details, not the plan view ---
    always review all detail sheets

-   Forgetting pipe bedding and trench backfill in the utility take-off

-   Not accounting for swell factor in excavation (bank CY vs. loose CY)

-   Confusing sanitary sewer and storm drainage --- they are separate
    systems with different materials and standards

-   Ignoring the specifications --- the specs define quality and
    sometimes add work not obvious from the drawings

-   Not including mobilization, bonds, permits, and testing in the
    estimate scope

*This guide is intended as a professional reference for reading civil
engineering drawings and performing material take-offs. Always verify
quantities with a licensed professional for formal bidding or permitting
purposes.*
